<br>
If you can't split a bunch of mobs, and the group is getting aggro'd, I've always thought the druid should evac and you could stay behind and FD.  <br>
<br>
Is that true?  I ask because it seems like both ways make people unhappy.  If I try to run over and get close enough to the monk to pick him up in evac, someone yells, no, just go!  If I evac from where I'm standing, someone says, no, the monk's not in range!<br>
<br>
I'm getting sort of frustrated, because whichever I pick I end up apologizing profusely.  Should the monk let me know if his FD is broken, will that help?  Do FD'd monks get picked up when there is an evac?  Help me out here.<br>
<br>
Thanks in advance, <p><font color=green face="ARIAL, HELVETICA, LUCIDA SANS"><B>Gwion Llewellyn</B></font><BR> Level, um, 39<BR>Useful druid of Tunare!<BR>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub76.ezboard.com/brandomacts.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=gaffanfallenoak>Gaffan Fallenoak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><b>RA Member<br><font color=red>Gourmet Medal of Baking<br>Forged Medal of Blacksmithing<br>Distilled Medal of Brewing<br>Ceramic Medal of Pottery<br>Embroidered Medal of Tailoring<br>Blurred Medal of Alcohol Tolerance</font><b></span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/4/01 12:11:17 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Monks, help me out here!</span><hr size=1> There's a lot of factors in play here.<br>
<br>
If the monk is close enough for the evac, it wont matter if hes FD or not. However usually if the monk is FD off somewhere, its going to be a lot further than the evac's range.<br>
<br>
Usually when you have to evac, its because of a bad pull, and the monk is already back with the group.  If you are getting aggro'd from the pull, chances are the monk is fairly closeby. In a situation where the monk is not with the group (hes out pulling, the room repops, you're group is getting swarmed), I would say announce you are going to evac, and give the monk a few seconds to FD off any mobs and scamper back. If there is not enough time for either the warning or the monk to get back, I would say evac without the monk.  <br>
<br>
Now that does sound kind of harsh, but here is why.<br>
<br>
A monk is going to be able to get himself out of any mess. He can feign/flop to the zone by himself, and be completly safe. <br>
<br>
There are a few zones where this would be rather difficult. But in a circumstance where I can get 5 of my party out alive, or we are all going to die, I'll go for the 5.  Makes getting that one person's body back a much easier task.<br>
<br>
Folks might complain about it.  Most monks (the good ones at least) won't.  Chances are they'll be sitting at the zone line, waiting on you by the time you get back.  And if your group complains, well tell them 'I can get the 5 of us out, or we are all going to die. You're choice. You have 5 seconds.'  <br>
<br>
Just some late night ramblings.<br>
<br>
Gaffan<br>
/ramblemodestuckintheonposition <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub76.ezboard.com/ukaral2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Karal2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><b><font color=yellow>RA Council Member</font><br><b><font color=blue>Administrator<br>Website Coordinator<br><font color=red>Ethical Medal of Action</font></span><br>  Posts: 384<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/4/01 1:16:18 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Monks, help me out here!</span><hr size=1> Not a Monk, but have to agree with Gaffan.  Basic policy in Meriel &amp; Co. (tm), is if evac is called then try to get close to the evac. If not we get as many out as possible to minimize the CR. We even go for individual gates if needed. The idea is to get as many folks out as possible. And our saying is &quot;There is no such thing as a bad evac call&quot;. Learn it, Love it, Live it. <p>Gorte McGinty<BR>
